Predicting the March Madness Bracket¶

Analysis by Alexander Tanimoto¶

Introduction¶

The NCAA Division I men's basketball tournament, otherwise branded as NCAA March Madness, is a 68 team tournament that determines the NCAA Division I national champion for college basketball. First, the Selection Committee selects 68 teams to participate in the tournament, ranking each from 1 to 68. Based on the rankings, the committee then divides the teams into four regions: East, South, Midwest, and West. In each region, teams are seeded from No. 1 to No. 16. As of 2011, eight teams will share a seed numbering with another team in the same region, and they will compete in a First Four round. This round returns four victorious teams, leaving 64 teams remaining and thus the standard single-elimination bracket. More information about the tournament can be found here.

Here is an illustration of what the March Madness bracket looks like. This is the final bracket for the 2022 March Madness tournament (which I will do my best to replicate later in the analysis). This image was taken from the official NCAA website.

Each year the challenge takes place, NCAA hosts the official bracket challenge before the tournament, allowing fans to predict the outcome of every game. Third party websites like ESPN and CBS Sports also host the challenge. While a seemingly trivial challenge, this tournament attracts over 35 million participants each year. The investment guru Warren Buffet himself initiated a bracket challenge in 2014 for employees of Berkshire Hathaway, promising to pay an employee that predicted every outcome correctly \$1 million every year, for life. Even though the odds of predicting each game correctly are astronomically small (1 in $2^{63}$ for 63 games, not including the First Four), I imagine most participants go into the challenge believing that their bracket will be the one. I believe the adrenaline rush of potentially achieving such an improbable feet is what makes this challenge so popular. The rise of sports betting has certainly aided in its popularity, as now many participants have a monetary incentive to predict correctly.

I am no exception to the madness that consumes the March Madness challenge. Last year, I participated in University of Maryland's Bracket Challenge for University Honors on ESPN. While I was unsuccessful in placing, I came out of the challenge more motivated than every to win a free pair of AirPods. Next time, I'll have a secret weapon unthinkable to everyone else: a model to predict the tournament for me.

My model is the result of doing a walkthrough of Kaggle's March Madness Learning Mania competition.

Datasets¶

Since 2015, Kaggle has hosted the March Madness Learning Mania competition, allowing machine learning enthusiasts to predict the outcome of the year's tournament (they also host one for women as well here). I am fortunate to have all the data I need to conduct the analysis I need from the datasets provided by Kaggle. Datasets can be found here, which also provide more information about the datasets if necessary. Note that as this analysis occurs after the tournament, we will be using datasets under Stage 2. Also note that not all datasets will be relevant for this analysis.

Before I go into depth with the datasets, we need to import pandas to read the CSV data files. The pandas library is an essential library for data science techniques. For full documentation details, see here.

Teams¶

One of the attached datasets is MTeams.csv, which stores all Division-I men's basketball teams ever recorded. Hence, it may include former D1 teams that were removed from the list. This will serve as a lookup table, i.e. if we need to look up a team name when primarily working with team IDs.

  • LastD1Season - The last season (or 2022 if current) the team was a D1 team. Again, not important for analysis.

Here's an important note. Remember how the tournament begins with 68 teams. Each team could play 67 possible teams. This dataset is actually predicting the probability of a team winning for every single possible matchup. There are 68 * 67 / 2 = 2278 possible matchups, so that is the number of rows we want in our dataset.

Data Preprocessing¶

Four Factors¶

If you looked at the MRegularSeasonDetailedResults.csv dataset, you'll notice how many stats we have for one game alone. Fortunately, we won't look at every one of them. Not only would that be an infeasible number of features to study, but having too features increases the model complexity and would lead to overfitting.

One way to predict the outcome would be to look at a strength of a team and then compare the rating of two teams. Creating a raating system, however, is beyond the scope of this project. We are not really concerned with looking at the strength of individual teams, but rather how the team stats interact with each other. For example, maybe a rating system rates Team A higher than Team B when looking at a certain set of team stats, but based on how a different set of team stats compare, Team B may be suited to beat Team A. We are more concerned with the latter: how the team stats compare in the matchup.

For each team, we will be using a philosophy called Four Factors to determine the strength of each basketball team. This philosophy was introduced by Dean Oliver, who claimed that these four factors were what determined basketball success (eight since we apply each to both offense and defense equally), along with their weights as to how much they each contributed to success. We are not worried about the weights for this project, because technically this is what our machine learning model will try to figure out. For more information, look here.

  • Shooting (40%, 20% each for offense and defense)
  • Turnovers (25%, 12.5% each)
  • Rebounding (20%, 10% each)
  • Free Throws (15%, 7.5% each)

Many rating systems use a combination of point differentials and strength of victory when accounting for the strength of teams. I think the Four Factors helps explain these two features pretty well. The four factors are what explain point differential. In terms of strength of victory, I want you to imagine the difference between the NBA playoffs and a street basketball tournament. Both may have similar point differentials and strength of victory stats due to the teams in the respective tournament. However, the NBA tournmanet probably features, for example, much better shooting efficiency and many less turnovers.

This is another reason why I want to use the Four Factors rather than a rating system: it allows us to analyze more features across teams than just point differential and strength of victory, and thus makes for a more interesting model.

Shooting¶

The factor is measured by Effective Field Goal Percentage (EFGP). The formula for both offense and defense is given as: EFGP = (FGM + 0.5 * FG3M) / FGA. The goal is to maximize EFGP for offense (OEFGP) and minimize EFGP for defense (DEFGP).

Turnovers¶

The factor is measured by the Turnover Percentage (TOP). The formula for both offense and defense is given as: TOP = TO / (FGA + 0.44 * FTA + TO). The goal is to now minimize TOP for offense (OTOP) and maximize TOP for defense (DTOP).

Rebounding¶

The factor is measured by rebounding percentages for both offense and defense (ORP and DRP, respectively). The formulas are as follows:

  • ORP = OR / (OR + Opp DR)
  • DRP = DR / (DR + Opp OR)

This time we want to maximize both percentages.

Free Throws¶

This factor is underratedly important. Being able to draw fouls and get to the line is an important skill of basketball. Of course, making the shots are also important. And on the other hand, you rather not have the majority of the opponent's shots come from free throws. For both offense and defense, the formula is the percentage of free throws made out of field goals attempted, which I will dub the free throw factor because I am that creative: FTF = FTM / FGA. The goal is to maximize the offensive FTF (OFTF) and minimize the defensive FTF (DFTF).

Based on the data we are trying to collect to calculate the eight factors, we need to accumulate the following team and opponent stats for the season:

  • FGM
  • FGA
  • FG3M
  • FTM
  • FTA
  • OR
  • DR
  • TO

From here on out, we aggregate the team stats for all teams in the tournament for the given season. First we define a helper function to aggregate team stats for the season from a given game.

In [10]:
def agg_game_stats(season_stats, team_id, game_index, t, o):
    '''
    This function will aggregate the team stats for the team identified by team_id in the season_stats dictionary parameter,
    based on the game identified by the game_index parameter. It does this by retrieving the appropriate column for the stats
    in the box_scores DataFrame. Note that t = team result ('W' or 'L'), o = opponent result.
    '''
    
    def agg_team_opp_stat(stat):
        '''
        This local function aggregates a season stat for both the team and opponent
        '''
        
        season_stats[team_id][f'T{stat}'] += box_scores[f'{t}{stat}'][game_index]
        season_stats[team_id][f'O{stat}'] += box_scores[f'{o}{stat}'][game_index]
    
    # Aggregate for eight stats, both for team and opponent
    agg_team_opp_stat('FGM')
    agg_team_opp_stat('FGA')
    agg_team_opp_stat('FGM3')
    agg_team_opp_stat('FTM')
    agg_team_opp_stat('FTA')
    agg_team_opp_stat('OR')
    agg_team_opp_stat('DR')
    agg_team_opp_stat('TO')
In [11]:
def calc_efgp(season_stats, team_id, p):
    '''
    Returns the effective field goal percentage given by the perspective passed in as 'p' (team or opponent).
    '''
    
    return (season_stats[team_id][f'{p}FGM'] + 0.5 * season_stats[team_id][f'{p}FGM3']) / season_stats[team_id][f'{p}FGA']
In [12]:
def calc_top(season_stats, team_id, p):
    '''
    Returns the turnover percentage given by the perspective passed in as 'p' (team or opponent).
    '''
    
    return (season_stats[team_id][f'{p}TO'] / 
            (season_stats[team_id][f'{p}FGA'] + 0.44 * season_stats[team_id][f'{p}FTA'] + season_stats[team_id][f'{p}TO']))
In [13]:
def calc_rp(season_stats, team_id, m0):
    '''
    Returns the rebound percentage for mode 'm0' (offense or defense).
    '''
    
    # Define opponent mode opposite to team
    m1 = 'D' if m0 == 'O' else 'O'
    
    return season_stats[team_id][f'T{m0}R'] / (season_stats[team_id][f'T{m0}R'] + season_stats[team_id][f'O{m1}R'])
In [14]:
def calc_ftf(season_stats, team_id, p):
    '''
    Returns the free throw factor given by the perspective passed in as 'p'.
    '''
    
    return season_stats[team_id][f'{p}FTM'] / season_stats[team_id][f'{p}FGA']

Now for the actual aggregation algorithm.

In [15]:
# Aggregate stats for each seed, for each season since 2003
for season in tourney_seeds[tourney_seeds['Season'] >= 2003]['Season'].unique():
    
    # Get all unique teams in tourney for season
    tourney_team_ids = set(tourney_seeds[tourney_seeds['Season'] == season]['TeamID'].unique())
    
    # Store aggregation of season stats for each team in dictionary (includes opponent data)
    # The first letter in each stat is either a 'T' (for team) or an 'O' (for opponent)
    season_stats = dict()
    for tourney_team_id in tourney_team_ids:
        season_stats[tourney_team_id] = {
            'TFGM' : 0,
            'OFGM' : 0,
            'TFGA' : 0,
            'OFGA' : 0,
            'TFGM3': 0,
            'OFGM3': 0,
            'TFTM' : 0,
            'OFTM' : 0,
            'TFTA' : 0,
            'OFTA' : 0,
            'TOR'  : 0,
            'OOR'  : 0,
            'TDR'  : 0,
            'ODR'  : 0,
            'TTO'  : 0,
            'OTO'  : 0
        }
    
    # For each game during the regular season, accumulate into team stats for season
    for game_index in box_scores[box_scores['Season'] == season].index:
        w_team_id, l_team_id = box_scores['WTeamID'][game_index], box_scores['LTeamID'][game_index]
        
        # Aggregate winning team stats if winning team is seed
        if w_team_id in tourney_team_ids:
            agg_game_stats(season_stats, w_team_id, game_index, 'W', 'L')
        
         # Aggregate losing team stats if losing team is seed
        if l_team_id in tourney_team_ids:
            agg_game_stats(season_stats, l_team_id, game_index, 'L', 'W')
    
    # Append to lists in order of seed
    for seed_index in tourney_seeds[tourney_seeds['Season'] == season].index:
        seed, tourney_team_id = tourney_seeds['Seed'][seed_index], tourney_seeds['TeamID'][seed_index]
        
        # Append data to identify team
        # Accessing team name requires a lookup in the teams DataFrame
        seasons.append(season)
        seeds.append(seed)
        team_ids.append(tourney_team_id)
        team_names.append(teams[teams['TeamID'] == tourney_team_id]['TeamName'].values[0])
        
        # Append stats for team
        oefgp.append(calc_efgp(season_stats, tourney_team_id, 'T'))
        defgp.append(calc_efgp(season_stats, tourney_team_id, 'O'))
        otop.append(calc_top(season_stats, tourney_team_id, 'T'))
        dtop.append(calc_top(season_stats, tourney_team_id, 'O'))
        orp.append(calc_rp(season_stats, tourney_team_id, 'O'))
        drp.append(calc_rp(season_stats, tourney_team_id, 'D'))
        oftf.append(calc_ftf(season_stats, tourney_team_id, 'T'))
        dftf.append(calc_ftf(season_stats, tourney_team_id, 'O'))

Tournament Games¶

The next DataFrame we will create is the dataset of interest for machine learning. For each historical tournament since 2003 (so pre-2022), we will store for each tournament game, the differences in team stats across the season, as well as the actual result of the matchup. To understand the differences in team stats, remember how the games will be identified: using the SSSS_XXXX_YYYY format earlier. So the difference in team stats is the team stat for XXXX - team stat for YYYY. To illustrate with an example, if the difference in offensive rebounding percentage is positive, then XXXX has a larger offensive rebounding percentage than YYYY, and if it is negative, then YYYY has a larger offensive rebounding percentage than XXXX.

Now the differences in team stats are what are called features. These are the independent variables, the ones that our model will use to make predictions. Meanwhile, the result of the matchup is the target. This is the dependent variable, the one our model is trying to predict. Hence, our model is using the differences in team differentials to predict the result of the matchup. The result will be encoded as 0 or 1, where 1 means that team XXXX won, and 0 means that team YYYY won. More information about features and targets can be found here.

First we define the columns we need for our DataFrame.

I'm going to use a helper function that appends the appropriate values to each of the feature lists. The reason will become more clear later, but essentially we will be using this function in more than one place.

In [22]:
def add_features(season, team1_id, team2_id):
    '''
    This function appends to both the list of matchup IDs and the lists storing the differences in team differentials.
    A difference in team differentials is given as: team differential for min_team_id - team differential for max_team_id.
    
    Note that the target list is not used in this function, because the two DataFrames that call this function will use
    different target variables.
    '''
    
    # DataFrames for detailed stats for given team and season
    team1_id_stats = detailed_tourney_seeds[(detailed_tourney_seeds['Season'] == season) & (detailed_tourney_seeds['TeamID'] == team1_id)]
    team2_id_stats = detailed_tourney_seeds[(detailed_tourney_seeds['Season'] == season) & (detailed_tourney_seeds['TeamID'] == team2_id)]
    
    # All matchup IDs follow the same format
    # Also append to deconstructed ID lists
    ids.append(f'{season}_{team1_id}_{team2_id}')
    seasons.append(season)
    teams1.append(team1_id_stats['TeamName'].values[0])
    teams2.append(team2_id_stats['TeamName'].values[0])
    
    # Append to difference lists (team1_id stat - team2_id stat)    
    oefgp.append(team1_id_stats['OEFGP'].values[0] - team2_id_stats['OEFGP'].values[0])
    defgp.append(team1_id_stats['DEFGP'].values[0] - team2_id_stats['DEFGP'].values[0])
    otop.append(team1_id_stats['OTOP'].values[0] - team2_id_stats['OTOP'].values[0])
    dtop.append(team1_id_stats['DTOP'].values[0] - team2_id_stats['DTOP'].values[0])
    orp.append(team1_id_stats['ORP'].values[0] - team2_id_stats['ORP'].values[0])
    drp.append(team1_id_stats['DRP'].values[0] - team2_id_stats['DRP'].values[0])
    oftf.append(team1_id_stats['OFTF'].values[0] - team2_id_stats['OFTF'].values[0])
    dftf.append(team1_id_stats['DFTF'].values[0] - team2_id_stats['DFTF'].values[0])

Great! Now we can actually construct the data for our DataFrame. Note that the result is done separate from the function because the second time we call the function, we will not keep track of the result.

In [23]:
# Iterate through all tournament games since 2003
for result_index in tourney_results[tourney_results['Season'] >= 2003].index:
    season = tourney_results['Season'][result_index]
    team_ids = (tourney_results['WTeamID'][result_index], tourney_results['LTeamID'][result_index])
    team1_id, team2_id = min(team_ids), max(team_ids)
    
    # Add matchup ID and features for tournament game
    add_features(season, team1_id, team2_id)
    
    # Encode the result as 1 (if min_id won) or 0 (if min_id lost)
    # Also append to winners for data representation
    results.append(1 if team1_id == team_ids[0] else 0)
    winners.append(teams[teams['TeamID'] == team_ids[0]]['TeamName'].values[0])

We now have our dataset of interest that will be used for machine learning purposes. A breakdown of the variables are shown below.

  • ID - A key identifying the tournament matchup, in the format SSSS_XXXX_YYYY, explained earlier in the analysis.
  • Season - The season the tournament took place.
  • Team1 - The name of the team with the smaller team ID (the XXXX).

  • OEFGP/DEFGP - Difference in offensive/defensive effective field goal percentages.
  • OTOP/DTOP - Difference in offensive/defensive turnover percentages.
  • ORP/DRP - Difference in offensive/defensive rebounding percentages.
  • OFTF/DFTF - Difference in offensive/defensive field goal factors.
  • Result - A numerical value 0 or 1 to indicate the result of the matchup.
    • 1 = Team1 won
    • 0 = Team2 won
  • Winner - The name of the team that won the matchup.

def scatter(feature):
    '''
    This function creates a custom scatter plot showcasing the chosen feature variable against the result of the matchup.
    '''
    
    # Set independent variable based on feature passed
    x = detailed_tourney_results[feature]
    
    # Construct scatter plot
    plt.scatter(x, y)
    plt.title(f'Result vs. {feature}')
    plt.xlabel(f'{feature}')
    plt.ylabel('Result')
    plt.show()

Offensive Effective Field Goal Percentage¶

In [31]:

Seems like having a better effective field goal percentage on offense is strongly correlated with winning the matchup. This makes sense; the more frequently you make your field goals, the more likely you are to win.

In [32]:
scatter('DEFGP')

Similarly, having a better effective field goal percentage on defense is strongly correlated with winning the matchup. This may be underratedly important, but often times limiting the effective field goal percentage of the opponent is a result of having a stingy defense that prevents openings to shoot.

Offensive Turnover Percentage¶

In [33]:
scatter('OTOP')

Limiting the turnover percentage on offensive is strongly correlated with winning. This should be fairly obvious; it's hard to win when your team is constantly turning the ball over.

Defensive Turnover Percentage¶

In [34]:

This time, the correlation between turnover percentage on defense and winning is much weaker. This suggests that perhaps turnovers reflect more poorly on poor ball handling skills by the team that committed the turnover than well on the team that benefited from the turnover.

Offensive Rebound Percentage¶

In [35]:
scatter('ORP')

There seems to be a strong correlation between offensive rebounding percentage and winning. Commonly known for creating second chance points, this would make sense as by giving yourself more chances to score, the more likely you are to score.

Defensive Rebound Percentage¶

In [36]:
scatter('DRP')

The correlation between defensive rebounding percentage and winning seems to be weak, but still existant. This could because in general, defensive rebounds are the expected rebounds. Offensive rebounds are just something extra, and reflects an extraordinary skill.

Offensive Free Throw Factor¶

In [37]:
scatter('OFTF')

The correlation seems to be a little weak with the offensive free throw factor and winning. Perhaps the free throw factor is more a sign of negligence by the other team.

Defensive Free Throw Factor¶

In [38]:
scatter('DFTF')

The correlation between the defensive free throw factor and winning seems stronger here. This supports our observation from looking at the offensive free throw factor: more a sign of negligence to allow free throws than skill to get the free throws.

Observations¶

In all the scatter plots, there is a relationship (the strength of the relationships varying significantly in strength) between the difference in the differential stat and the result of the matchup. For example, difference in point differentials seems to have a positive correlation with the result of the matchup (so a positive difference correlates to winning), while a difference in turnover differentials seems to have a negative correlation with the result of the matchup (negative difference correlates to winning).

Feature Selection¶

Before we can build our regression model, we need to decide which features (team stats) we want to include in our model. While it may turn out that we use all eight factors, it is always best practice when developing a machine learning model that we at least employ feature selection methods to determine which input variables that will be relevant to building the model. What is so bad about having too many input variables? By increasing the complexity of the model, it may lead to overfitting as the model may consider features that are not relevant to the target variable.

Based on the scatter plots, the regression that would best suit this problem would be to showcase a logistic regression problem. The feature variables are numerical, numerical differences in team stats. The target variable is a discrete variable because it can only take two values for the result: 0 (loss) or 1 (win). But it is still a regression model because the ultimate goal is to predict a numeric probability of a win.

We will be using Spearman's rank coefficient as our feature selection method. I added a chart below, but remember that we are working with a regression predictive modeling problem: the probability that the team with the lower ID in the matchup wins. Hence our output is a numeric probability. Our input variables are numeric (we are dealing with basketball stats). Since logistic regression is a nonlinear correlation, we end up using Spearman's. Specifically, we will be calculating Spearman's coefficients for each of the features (basketball team stats) against the target variable, the result. For more information on selecting the feature selection method, look here.

Spearman's Rank Correlation¶

We have to ask ourselves the question: how will we use the Spearman coefficients for feature selection? We aren't exactly interested in the coefficient values (ranging from -1 to +1 to indicate strength of relationship), but rather the significance of those values. We need the p-values of these correlation values -- the probability of observing values as extreme or more given that the null hypothesis (no relationship between the difference in differential stat and the result) is true. And to do that, we need to use the spearmanr function from scipy to get not only the coefficient, but the p-value associated with it as well. The scipy library is important for conducting various mathematical and statistical analyses, such as conducting a statistical test as we are doing here. Here is the scipy documentation if you are interested.

Let's import scipy first.

In [39]:
from scipy import stats

Let's create new DataFrame to showcase all the Spearman coefficients, as well as their p-values.

In [40]:
# Store Spearman correlation between columns
corrs = []

# Store p-values for correlation values
p_vals = []
In [41]:
# Iterate through every feature
for feature in features:
    
    # Find coorelation coefficient and associated p-value
    corr, p_val = stats.spearmanr(detailed_tourney_results[feature], detailed_tourney_results['Result'])
    
    # Append to lists storing entry values for DataFrame
    corrs.append(corr)
    p_vals.append(p_val)
In [42]:
# Create the DataFrame for the correlation pairings
corr_mat = pd.DataFrame({
    'Feature'    : features,
    'Correlation': corrs,
    'p-value'    : p_vals
})

Holdout Validation¶

We need to split the data set into training and testing data. When we actually submit our model to the Kaggle tournament, we will train on all the data available because the Kaggle submission will test on data that none of our datasets have access to. However, when we want to evaulate the effectiveness of our model, like right now, it is absolutely necessary to split the data. Otherwise, we would be evaluating the effectiveness of our model to predict data it has already been trained on, and we would have severe overfitting. For more information, check out here.

In [45]:
# Define independent variables
X = detailed_tourney_results[features]

Conclusion¶

When I submitted submission.csv to the Kaggle tournament, I got a log loss of 0.66941. If we were to look at the leaderboard, it would turn out that I would rank 553rd out of 930 teams. This is nothing too great, as it is below average in the tournament. However, the purpose of this project was not to create the best model of all time, but rather to demonstrate the data pipeline: the preprocessing and exploratory analysis we need to take to develop a working model.

There are several flaws with my approach. I may have implied this in the beginning, but we don't directly account for strength of opponent when we look at the four factors. How would we go about doing this next time? Perhaps, for example, when we are calculating offensive field goal percentage for a team in a given game, we need to compare that percentage with the offensive field goal percentage that the opponent gives up on average. That way, we get a fixed benchmark to evaluate the team against other teams that have played the opponent, and hence a better basis for calculating relative strength of the team in one or more stats.

Another flaw that I made was that I assumed that each factor was independent of each other when building my machine learning model. It is important that the features used in training a model are independent of each other, and this is a feature called multicollinearity. In reality, however, the features do interact with each other to a small extent. For example, offensive rebounds may lead to a better offensive effective field goal percentage. The factors are calculated in a manner that the factors interact with each other as little as possible, but there is always some correlation.

Nevertheless, this is the whole data pipeline for building a machine learning model. First we conduct data preprocessing with the datasets to get a data table in the format of data we need to make predictions. Next we do some exploratory analysis to look at which features correlate with the target variable and select our features from there. Then we would try different machine learning algorithms that could potentially best capture the relationship between the features and the target variable, making sure to split the data into training and testing sets beforehand. I only did logistic regression for this tutorial since I felt this regression technique modeled the relationship to a T. Last we evaluate each algorithm, see which one yields the most accurate results, and build a final machine learning model that trains on all the data, because from now we will be testing on data the machine learning model has never seen.

Again, here is the Kaggle challenge if you are interested in trying this experiment for yourself. I found this tutorial from Kaggle especially useful in getting yourself acquainted with the pipeline for building machine learning models, and should give you a foothold into building many simple machine learning models. Happy training!
